From fae242772ccdf7f6546fb110885b02dffe717f2c Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: dfattal <dfattal@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 19 Jul 2026 18:35:06 +0900
Subject: inline-3d(#22): best-overlap overlay match, clipped-overlay source
 region, probes
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Three related correctness/diagnostic changes on the overlay path. Neither
fix is credited with resolving an observed symptom — both were found while
chasing the fast-scroll header artifact, which turned out to be elsewhere
(see below) — but both are correct on their own terms and have run on
hardware all day without regression.

1. best_match now picks the BEST-overlapping candidate rather than the last
   one over the 70% bar. The target is the Blink main-thread rect trailing
   the impl scroll by ~1 frame, so a fast scroll can drag it far enough that
   several quads qualify at once, and last-wins then selected by iteration
   order. Ties still keep the topmost, so the single-candidate steady state
   is unchanged by construction.

   Also documents why a size-similarity guard does NOT belong here: the
   target is visible_bounds (window-CLIPPED) while the quad rect is
   UNCLIPPED, so a partly-scrolled-off element legitimately reports e.g.
   1235x489 against 1235x696. An earlier guard rejected exactly those valid
   matches.

2. The overlay atlas mapped the WHOLE source image onto a destination rect
   already clipped to the window, rescaling any overlay that is partly
   off-screen. Now sub-regions the source by the same fraction the clip took
   off the destination — the fix bug B applied to the canvas path.

3. Two throttled VLOG(1) probes distinguishing "the global-overlay exclusion
   is missing this frame" from "a declared overlay went unmatched over a 3D
   canvas". These paid for themselves: they are what localised the residual
   fast-scroll header blow-up to a truncated exclusion RECT (true 3825x142
   device px, observed tail 57..99) rather than anything on this path. Kept
   deliberately — VLOG(1) is inert without --v=1.

